==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smirk
<hw>Smirk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Smirked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Smirking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>smirken</ets>, ASS.
<ets>smercian</ets>, <ets>smearcian</ets>; cf. MHG. <ets>smieren</ets>,
<ets>smielen</ets>, to smile. See <er>Smile</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To smile in an affected or conceited manner; to
smile with affected complaisance; to simper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smirk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smirk
<hw>Smirk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A forced or affected smile; a
simper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bride, all <qex>smirk</qex> and blush, had just entered.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smirk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smirk
<hw>Smirk</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Nice,; smart; spruce; affected;
simpering.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧So <xex>smirk</xex>, so smooth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smirkingly</ent>⟦br⟧
